'''Elisabeth Larsson''' (born December 30, 1971) is a Swedish [[applied mathematics|applied mathematician]] and [[numerical analysis|numerical analyst]]. She is a senior lecturer in the Department of Information Technology of [[Uppsala University]], and the director of the Uppsala Multidisciplinary Centre for Advanced Computational Science.{{r|profile}}

==Research==
Larsson's research involves the applications of [[radial basis function]]s to [[scientific computing]]. It has included work on the propagation of sound waves through water, pricing of financial options, and simulation of the earth's climate.{{r|gg}}

==Education and career==
Larsson was born on December 30, 1971{{r|cv}} in [[Ljusdal]], and went to high school in Ljusdal.{{r|gg}} She earned a master's degree in engineering physics at Uppsala University in 1994, and completed a Ph.D. in [[numerical analysis]] at Uppsala in 2000. Her dissertation was ''Domain Decomposition and Preconditioned Iterative Methods for the Helmholtz Equation''.{{r|cv}} Her doctorate was supervised by Kurt Otto, with {{ill|Bengt Fornberg|fr}} as outside examiner.{{r|diss}}

She became a junior researcher in the Department of Information Technology at Uppsala in 2001, and an assistant professor in 2007. She was promoted to senior lecturer in 2011.{{r|cv}}

==Recognition==
In 2007, Larsson was one of two winners of the Göran Gustafsson Award for outstanding young Swedish scientists.{{r|gg}}

